variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Valle","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Manuel, Luis, Ramon, Carlos, Jesus, Jorge, Roberto, Mario, Rafael, Francisco.  Italian Antonio, Angelo, Heriberto, Pio, Romeo, Aldo, Clemente, Leonardo, Marcello, Marco, Marco Antonio, Camillo.","Spanish and Italian: topographic name from <i>valle</i> ‘valley’ (from Latin <i>vallis</i>), or a habitational name from any of the many places called with this word. This surname is also found in Corsica and southern France. Compare Spanish   Del Valle   and   De Valle  , Italian   Lavalle   1.","French (<b>Vallé</b>): variant of <b>Vallée</b> ‘valley’ (see   Vallee  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Val","meanings":["Spanish: variant of   Valle  , from <i>val</i>, a variant of <i>valle</i> ‘valley’. Compare   Delval  .","Galician and Portuguese: topographic name for someone who lived in a valley, <i>val</i> (compare 3 below). Compare also   Doval  .","French and Haitian: topographic name for someone who lived in a valley, (Old) French <i>val</i> (originally feminine, later masculine; compare   Vallee  ), from Latin <i>vallis</i> (feminine). Compare   Duval   and   Laval  ."]},{"name":"Valli","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Antonio, Caesar, Carmela, Dario, Gildo, Guido, Luigi.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of   Valle   or a habitational name from a place called with this word, as for example Valli del Pasubio or Valli dei Signori.","Italianized form of Slovenian <b>Valič</b>: patronymic from a short form of the personal name <i>Valentin</i> (see   Valentine  )."]},{"name":"Lavalle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo (5), Dino (3), Santo (3), Antonio (2), Salvatore (2), Aldo, Carmel, Duilio, Egidio, Enrico, Luigi.","Italian (also <b>La Valle</b>): topographic name from <i>valle</i> ‘valley’ (from Latin <i>vallis</i>), or a habitational name from any of the many places called with this word. Compare   Valle  .","French (<b>Lavallé</b>): variant of <b>Lavallée</b> ‘the valley’ (see   Lavallee  ) and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]},{"name":"Valletta","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Antimo, Antonio, Caesar, Carmine, Giovanni, Nicola, Rocco, Salvatore, Umberto, Vincenzo.","Italian (southern): from a diminutive of   Valle  ."]},{"name":"Vallone","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Pasquale, Salvatore, Vito, Gaetano, Lia, Sal, Angelo, Annamarie, Benedetta, Carmela, Carmelo, Carmin.","Italian:","from an augmentative of   Valle  ."]},{"name":"Del Valle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Manuel, Luis, Juan, Mario, Pedro, Francisco, Jorge, Angel, Miguel, Orlando.","Spanish: variant, with the preposition and definite article <i>del</i> ‘from the’, of   Valle   ‘valley’."]},{"name":"Valleau","meanings":["French: derivative of French <b>Vallé</b> (see   Valle  ) or <b>Vallée</b> ‘valley’ (see   Vallee  ).","History: This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America."]},{"name":"Vallario","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Pasquale, Salvatore, Lorenzo, Franco, Silvestro.","Italian (southern): from a derivative of   Valle  ."]},{"name":"Valla","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Antonio, Attilio, Marco.","Italian: variant of   Valle  .","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several places or farmsteads in Nordland named with the plural of Old Norse <i>vǫllr</i> ‘field, meadow’. Compare   Walla  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Boñar","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Bonner  .","Irish (Donegal): Scottish name adopted as a translation of Gaelic <b>Ó Cnáimhsighe</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cnáimhseach</i>’, a byname meaning ‘midwife’. This word seems to be a derivative of <i>cnámh</i> ‘bone’ (with the feminine ending <i>-seach</i>), but if so the reason for this is not clear.","Polish: from German <b>Bohner</b> or   Boner   ‘bean grower’."],"variants":[{"name":"Bonner","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>boner(e), bonour</i> ‘gentle, courteous’ (Old French <i>bonnaire</i>, shortened from <i>debonnaire</i>). This surname is also common in Ireland where it was adopted for <b>Ó Cnáimhsighe</b>, see   Bonar   2.","Welsh: Anglicized form of Welsh <i>ap Ynyr</i> ‘son of <i>Ynyr</i>’, a common medieval personal name derived from Latin <i>Honorius</i> with fused patronymic marker <i>(a)p</i>, normally voiced before a vowel.","German (also <b>Bönner</b>): from a short form of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Bonhard</i>, formed with the element <i>bon</i> ‘request, petition’ (compare Latin <i>bonus</i>). This surname is also found in Sweden."]}]},{"name":"Ramiro","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","me